    tern:instructions """<p>Extending instructions from Plot soil description module</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      Ensure the Plot selection and layout module has been completed to mark out
      the plot grid with sub- meter accuracy using the Trimble® R1.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the ‘Soils’ module and then the ‘Soil pit characterization’
      protocol in the App. The App will automatically record the Plot name,
      based on the established plot you are working in, the Protocol, and the
      Date.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Locate the southwest corner of the plot.</p></li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record the Type of soil observation being used (Appendix M). This should
      be ‘P’ (Soil pit) for pedologists or experience soil surveyors (continue
      with <u>Soil pit characterization and soil sample</u><u>collection</u> below), or ‘T’ (10 cm samples) extracted via ‘P’ (Soil
      pit) for less experienced field surveyors (skip to <u>Soil sample</u><u>collection</u>). Refer to pages 205–206 of the YB for further
      descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
<p style="color: orange">
  Soil pit characterization and soil sample collection
</p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record who the soil pit characterization is Characterized by from the
      drop-down list of personnel affiliated with your user login.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Dig a soil pit to 1 m+ deep just outside the southwest corner of plot.
      Place the spoil on a ground sheet to minimize disturbance and assist
      backfilling. Record the Depth of the soil pit.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If a depth of 1 m+ cannot be achieved after three attempts, record what
      digging was Stopped by (Appendix N) and the R horizon depth in meters.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess which face of the pit is best for photographing, taking into
      consideration angle of the sun and shadows. Position the pit tape on the
      left or right edge of the best face and select the 'Soil pit photo' button
      to capture an image using your device's camera.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Identify the soil horizons in the soil profile. Select the ‘Add soil
      horizon’ button to record soil profile data for the first soil horizon.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record the Horizon and Horizon suffix using the codes in Appendix O. Refer
      to pages 148–159 of the YB and the <u>Additional guidelines</u> below for
      further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record the Depth of the soil horizon in centimeters, including Upper and
      Lower.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record the Boundary between the horizon being assessed the
      horizon below, including the Distinctness and Shape of the boundary using
      the codes in Appendix P. Refer to pages 199–200 of the YB for further
      descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record Field texture, including the Grade, Qualification and
      Modifier using the codes in Appendix Q. Refer to pages 161–167 of the YB
      for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record matrix Color, including the Hue, Value and Chroma using
      the Munsell Soils Color Charts (Munsell Color 2009), and Moisture status
      using the codes in Appendix R. Moisten the soil if it is dry. Dry colors
      may also be recorded. Refer to Munsell Color (2009) and page 159 of the YB
      for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If present, assess and record Mottles, including their Type, Abundance,
      Size, Contrast, Color and Boundaries distinctness using the codes in
      Appendix S. Record multiple if present. Refer to pages 159– 161 of the YB
      for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If present, assess and record Coarse fragments, including their Abundance,
      Size, Shape, Lithology, Strength and Alteration using the codes in
      Appendix T. Record multiple if present. Refer to pages 139– 144, 209 and
      214 of the YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record Structure, including the Grade, Size, Type and Compound
      pedality using the codes in Appendix U. Record multiple if present (i.e.,
      largest peds parting to smaller sized peds down to the primary ped. Refer
      to pages 171–181 of the YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If present, assess and record Segregations, including their Abundance,
      Nature, Form, Size, Strength and Magnetic attributes using the codes in
      Appendix V. Record multiple if present. Refer to pages 195– 198 of the YB
      for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If present, assess and record Voids, including Cracks, Fine macropore
      abundance, Coarse macropore abundance and Mean macropore diameter using
      the codes in Appendix W. Record multiple if present. Refer to pages
      184–185 of the YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record Consistence, including soil Strength and Soil water
      status using the codes in Appendix X. Refer to pages 186–187 of the YB for
      further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If present, assess and record Pans, including Type, Cementation,
      Continuity and Structure using the codes in Appendix Y. Refer to pages
      192–195 of the YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record the Fabric using the codes in Appendix Z. Refer to pages
      181–182 of the YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      If present, assess and record Cutans, including Type, Abundance and
      Distinctness using the codes in Appendix AA. Refer to pages 182–183 of the
      YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record Field pH (to 0.5 of a unit) using a pH kit based on the
      specifications of Raupach and Tucker (1959). Portable pH meters may also
      be used. Refer to page 198 of the YB for further details.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record EC 1:5 (electrical conductivity) using a portable EC
      meter. Follow instructions for the meter being used.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Assess and record the Effervescence of carbonate in fine earth using 2–3
      drops of 1 Molar HCl and the codes in Appendix BB. Refer to page 198 of
      the YB for further descriptions.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Prepare a soil sample zip-lock bag for each 10 cm soil depth increment in
      the horizon that you are collecting a sample from. Use a permanent text to
      write the plot code, date of collection, horizon and soil depth increment.
      Place a barcode label on each sample bag in sequential order.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      For each 10 cm soil depth increment in the horizon, collect a 500 g soil
      sample and place into the applicable labeled zip-lock bag, avoiding
      disruption to any peds or aggregates as much as possible and taking care
      not to sample across horizons. Use the pit tape to determine the
      increments.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Record the Sample depth in centimeters, including Upper and Lower.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select the 'Scan barcode' button to scan the barcode label on the sample
      and link the sample to the horizon and the sample depth.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Repeat steps 23–26 for each 10 cm soil depth increment in the horizon that
      you are collecting a sample from.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Repeat steps 5–27 for each soil horizon down to a depth of 1 m+.</p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Store all samples together in a large plastic bag.</p></li>
  <li>
    <p>For clayey loams, assess and record Dispersion and Slaking:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Fill a tray with enough deionized water to cover peds.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Place a small dry ped into the deionized water for each soil depth
          increment of interest. Start at the top, like a clock, and continue
          clockwise to keep track of sample depths.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Score Dispersion and Slaking after at least 10 minutes using the codes
          in Appendix CC.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Score Dispersion again after 2 hours, or at least until after you have
          finished all other tasks in the Soils module, using the codes in
          Appendix CC.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          For any peds that don’t disperse, test a 5–10 mm sample from the soil
          bolus that was used for soil texturing (see step 9 above). This is
          equivalent to ‘remolding the sample’ and may help you to score the
          sample as either 0 or 1 for dispersion (see Appendix CC).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Record the Australian Soil Classification (ASC), including the Confidence
      level, Order, Suborder, Great group, Sub group and Family using the codes
      in Appendix DD, Appendix EE, Appendix FF and Appendix GG. To accurately
      categorize soils within the ASC requires the specialized skills of a
      pedologist and should not be attempted by inexperienced field surveyors.
      It will only be possible following all the non- essential descriptions
      under the soil characterization to 1 m+ depth. Refer to the third edition
      of The Australian Soil Classification for further descriptions (Isbell and
      The National Committee on Soil and Terrain 2016).
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Check the 'ASC needs to be determined back in the lab' checkbox if this is
      the case.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Record any Additional soil pit characterization comments.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Prior to backfilling, undertaken the <u>Soil bulk density protoco</u>l,
      which collects soil bulk density samples from an edge of the pit.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Select ‘Complete Soil pit characterization' to save the protocol and
      return to the Soils module.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
<p style="color: orange">Soil sample collection</p>
<ol>
